eioped >x cr.m*\n.J4O..US .11 to meet the ob\ntVMP- -d In ih* House of\n,vKpi oa AUMUJi* a,\n1067,\" Mr. Thompson said. No\none spoke against a National\nCultural Center in that debate.\n\"Everyone was for a national\ncultural center In the Nation\u2019s\nCapital. The opponents of the\nsite selected by the District of\nColumbia Auditorium Commis\nsion Insisted they were just as\ndedicated to the concept of a\ncenter as the proponents of the\nsite chosen by the Auditorium\nCommission.\nr \"They Insisted, however, that\n\u2018We can still have the center,\n1 and quicker, on one of several\nI available Government owned\naltea.\u2019 I agree with them.\nFoggy Bottom Opposition\n\"Among the opponents of the\n\u2022\u2022\u2022Foggy Bottom site were the\ni Washington Board of Trade\nI and the Federal City Council.\nI \"The Washington Board of\n'Trade\u2019s Auditorium Committee\nand It\u2019s co-ordinating Com\nmittee on tUe Future of Wash\nington. are much more inter\nesief* in a convention hall th<N*\nUkviwnal cultural mmimw. in\na paper prepared by John W.\nThompson, chairman of the\nlatter committee and preaident\nof The Eveniilg Star Broad\ncasting Co., and presented to\nthe Business Outlook Confer\nence of the Washington Board\nof Trade on January. M. 1958.\na preference was expressed for\nthe convention hall plan put\nforward by the District of Co\nlumbia Auditorium Commis\nsion.\n\"Interestingly enough, the\nCultural Development Commit\ntee of the Washington Board\nof Trade has been completely\nsilent In the matter but the\nevidence would seem to indicate\nthat If the kingmakers in the\nboard of trade permitted It to\nexpress an opinion It would\nfavor by compromise bill, H. R.\n\u2014RALEIGH HABERDASHER, WASHINGTON AND CHEVY CHASE-\nBible Seller's Charges j\nHold Prosnectin Beating\nJames Harris, 01, of the 1400 block of Fifteenth street N.W.\nwas held for the grand Jury yesterday on a charge of aaaaulting\na 73-year-old Bible salesman with a dangerous weapon\u2014his\nshod foot.\nThe salesman. George 8. Herfurth of 3707 Woodley place\nN.W., testified at a preliminary hearing In Municipal Court that\nhe was kicked and beaten by.\nthe defendant in an alley at\n1460 P street N.W. on January 8\nHe told the court he was\nhospitalised sight days with a\ngash over his left eye and a\nconcussion suffered from a kick;\nto the head.\nMr. Iftrfurth testified he met'\nHarris at the latter\u2019s third\nfloor apartment door and of\nfered to sell him a -Bible for\n\u266633-66, to be paid in total-\n0848. over the plan advanced\nby the District of Columbia\nAuditorium Commission\nmeats. He said Harris took the\nBible from him and closed the\ndoor.\nThe salesman testified he\ntried In vain to recover the\nBible through the aid of a Jani\ntor and then left the building\nto find police. He sold he\nnoticed Harris was following\nhim when he reached the\nground floor.\nHarris followed him until\nthey reached the alley. Mr.\nHerfurth testified, \u201cwhere he\npitched me in.\u201d Mr. Herfurth\njSpecial Research Fund\nTo Aid D. C. Agencies\nI A special research fund to\nbenefit Washington agencies has\nbeen established by the Eugene\nand Agnes E. Meyer Founda\ntion. to be administered by the\nBureau of Social Science Re\nsearch.\nDr. Robert T. Bower, bureau\ndirector, said the fund would\nfinance research projects for\nlocal organisations that have\nno money for-such studies.\nDr, Bower said all responsible\napplications for allocations will\nbe considered. Information may\nbe obtained from bureau head\nquarters at 3017 Connecticut\navenue N.W.\n=\u25a0*s*====:====\u2014*^^\nsaid. Harris fled after the bett\ning.\nThe defendant did not\ntestify. Judge John J. Malloy\ncontinued his bond at SI4OO.\nArtists to Exhibit\nAt Tea Sunday\nThe Washington Society of\nArtiste will exhibit during the\nfirst February meeting of the\nArt Club at a tea from 0 to\n0:30 p.m. Sunday.\nOther Art Club programs\nduring the month will be:\nThursday. February 0. 7:30\np.m.. author Patricia McOerr\nwill speak on her novel \"Mar\ntha, Martha?\u2019: Thursday, Feb\nruary 13. 7:80 pm., Edwin Da\nvis, pianist, will play; Tuesday,\nFebruary IS. 7 p.m.. Dr. Giles\nE. Dawson, curator of hooka fit\nFolger Shakespeare Library,\nwill speak, and Thursday Feb\nruary 20, 7:30 p.m\u201e a film will\nbe shown on the cosmic rays.\nThe 45th annual exhibition\nof the Landscape Club will be\ngin during a 6 to 6:30 pm. tea\nSunday. February 23. \u201cCity\nPlanning in Europe\u201d will be\nexplained at 7:30 pm. Thurs\nday, February 37.","height":"28839","width":"18190"}}
